  "prompt": "Why do some fish taste very fishy?",
  "response": "Some fish taste more \"fishy\" due to several factors:\n\n1. Freshness\n- Older fish develops stronger, more pungent flavors\n- As fish ages, oils break down and create a stronger fishy taste\n- Fresh fish should have a mild, clean flavor\n\n2. Fat content\n- Oily fish like mackerel, sardines, and salmon tend to have more pronounced fishy flavors\n- High fat content means more oils that can develop stronger tastes when not fresh\n\n3. Type of fish\n- Some species naturally have stronger flavors\n- Bluefish, mackerel, and herring are known for more intense tastes\n- Whitefish like cod or halibut typically have milder flavors\n\n4. Trimethylamine (TMA)\n- Compound produced when fish begins to spoil\n- Creates strong, unpleasant \"fishy\" smell and taste\n- Develops as bacteria break down fish proteins\n\n5. Handling and storage\n- Improper storage can accelerate fish spoilage\n- Exposure to warm temperatures increases bacterial growth\n- Poor handling can cause faster flavor deterioration\n\nTo reduce fishy taste, buy fresh fish, store it properly, and cook it quickly after purchasing.",
